</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."],"variants":[{"name":"Jordin","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."]},{"name":"Jordyn","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."]},{"name":"Jorden","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."]},{"name":"Jordon","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jordan Haccombe was born about 1235, in Haccombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom as the son of Stephen Haccombe and Mrs Stephen de Haccombe II. He married Cecily Penpol. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1287, at the age of 53, and was buried in Haccombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"ABT 1235–1287":"umbes 1235–1287","1235–1287":"1235–1287","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1258–1304":"1258–1304","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1304":"1304","before 1235":"enne 1235","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1287":"1287","ABT 1235":"umbes 1235","about 1258":"umbes 1258","1240":"1240","3 November 1263":"3. november 1263","Haccombe, Devonshire, England":"Haccombe, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haccombe, Devon, England":"Haccombe, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haccombe, Teignbridge District, Devon, England":"Haccombe, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"ABT 1235–1287":"noin 1235–1287","1235–1287":"1235–1287","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1258–1304":"1258–1304","1200–Male":"120